         b' status-publish format-standard hentry category-conference category-'
         b'event category-mobile category-privacy category-reputation category-'
         b'research category-trust" id="post-195">\n\t\t\t<h2>Intl Workshop on '
         b'Trust in Mobile Environments</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t'
         b'\t\t<p>Yesterday was the first International Workshop on Trust in '
         b'Mobile Environments (<a href="http://time08.cs.ucl.ac.uk/">TIME 2008'
         b'</a>), co-located with the <a href="http://www.ntnu.no/videre/konfer'
         b'anse/IFIPTM08/">IFIPTM 08</a> conference in Trondheim, Norway. The w'
         b'orkshop merged with the Workshop on Sustaining Privacy in Autonomous'
         b' Collaborative Environments (<a href="http://secml.otago.ac.nz/priva'
         b'cy2008/">SPACE</a>), and consisted of three sessions. Here is a brie'
         b'f summary on what we saw:<span id="more-195"></span></p>\n<p><str'
         b'ong>Keynote: <a href="http://www.cs.utsa.edu/~winsboro/">Will Winsbo'
         b'rough</a>, University of Texas at San Antonio</strong></p>\n<p><s'
         b'trong>Session 1: Privacy</strong></p>\n<p>There were two papers p'
         b'resented in the morning session: &#8220;Secure and Privacy-Preservin'
         b'g DRM For Mobile Devices with Web Service Security: An Experience Re'
         b'port&#8221; (Kleiner, Grittner, Kadenbach) and &#8220;Comprehensive '
         b'Analysis of Web Privacy and Anonymous Web Browsers: Are Next Generat'
         b'ion Services Based on Collaborative Filtering?&#8221; (Gulyas, Schul'
         b'cz, Imre)</p>\n<p>The whole issue of privacy seems to revolve aro'
         b'und conflicting interests: in DRM the content producers want to keep'
         b' the rights to their work (in order to provide fair distribution), w'
         b'hile mobile users may not want to be profiled according to their acc'
         b'ess to certification authorities. In web environments, users, advert'
         b'isers,\xc2\xa0 and e-commerce sites will want to dig into (or hide'
         b') the goldmine of user profiles for different reasons. The proposed '
         b'solutions seemed to revolve around anonymity: but to what extent is '
         b'<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Privacy">privacy</a> about hid'
         b'ing, and to what extent is it about information flow control?</p'
         b'>\n<p><strong>Session 2: Models</strong></p>\n<p>The second sessio'
         b'n dealt with different views of trust models, and there were three p'
         b'apers: my work, &#8220;Learning to Trust on the Move,&#8221; &#8220;'
         b'A Behavioural Model for Client Reputation&#8221; (Basu, Wakeman, Cha'
         b'lmers, Robinson), and &#8220;Towards User Driven Trust Modeling and '
         b'Management&#8221; (Z. Yan, Niemi)</p>\n<p>Perhaps the most intere'
         b'sting point of this session is the lack of consensus across differen'
         b't domains about what a trust model entails. While <a href="http://ww'
         b'w.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/n.lathia/publications/time08.html">my work</a> '
         b'argued that mobile-trust models can be casted into a learning proble'
         b'm (and thus quantity and quality of information available become the'
         b' key influential factors), Z. Yan&#8217;s work called for building t'
         b'rust-models with strong support from user-groups. Anirban Basu&#8217'
         b';s ongoing PhD work, on the other hand, described a distributed repu'
         b'tation-based system that can tackle problems like unsolicited e-mail'
         b'.</p>\n<p><strong>Session 3: Mobility</strong></p>\n<p>The last se'
         b'ssion shifted focus from trust to mobility. There were two presentat'
         b'ions: &#8220;Rethinking Network Mobility in Pervasive Markets: Model'
         b' and Trust&#8221; (Lu Yan), and &#8220;Validation of OLSR Routing Ta'
         b'ble Based on Trust Reasoning&#8221; (Adnane, Bidan, de Sousa).</'
         b'p>\n<p>I think Lu Yan gave the most interesting presentation of t'
         b'he whole workshop. His work focuses on how to model human motion usi'
         b'ng a bottom-up approach. Rather than defining characteristics of mob'
         b'ility, he starts from observations of how people move in the Camden '
         b'market, draws a number of similarities between those trajectories an'
         b'd the way foraging animals move, and can then build mobility models '
         b'based on this. Asmaa Adnane&#8217;s work was a follow up to work tha'
         b't <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2008/04/08/effectiveness-of-t'
         b'rust-reasoning-for-attack-detection-in-olsr/">appeared in this blog<'
         b'/a> previously: she discussed new attacks that her previous work cou'
         b'ld not detect, and a novel means of coping with them.</p>\n<p>Ove'
         b'rall, there were a lot of interesting topics discussed and issues ra'
         b'ised. To all participants: feel free to <a href="http://mobblog.cs.u'
         b'cl.ac.uk/how-to-subscribe/">join us</a> and contribute your thoughts'
         b' to this blog.</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetad'
